24
00:01:17,577 --> 00:01:19,670
<i>I'd say, "Morrie, that's disgusting. "</i>
<i>He'd say, "I'm sorry you think so.</i>

25
00:01:19,746 --> 00:01:22,738
<i>I also like cole slaw.</i>
<i>Can you handle cole slaw, Mitch?"</i>

26
00:01:22,816 --> 00:01:26,650
****<i>[Continues, Indistinct]</i>

27
00:01:26,719 --> 00:01:30,450
- Excuse me.
- <i>Near the top of the list</i>
<i>of things he loved was dancing.</i>

28
00:01:37,664 --> 00:01:40,827
- [Man Yelling]
- <i>He had his own way of dancing.</i>

29
00:01:40,900 --> 00:01:43,460
<i>He'd do the lindy</i>
<i>toJimi Hendrix.</i>

30
00:01:43,536 --> 00:01:47,097
<i>He'djitterbug to</i>...
<i>name a band</i>... <i>Nine Inch Nails.</i>

31
00:01:47,173 --> 00:01:49,801
- Pardon me. Here you go, boy.
- What you got, Professor?

32
00:01:49,876 --> 00:01:52,174
Hey, just put it on.
You're gonna love it.

33
00:01:52,245 --> 00:01:55,703
**<i>I can't top the letter "M"</i>
<i>You're not a</i>... ****

34
00:01:55,782 --> 00:01:59,013
[Music Changes,
Crowd Murmuring]

35
00:01:59,085 --> 00:02:01,053
Hey!

36
00:02:01,121 --> 00:02:04,215
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

37
00:02:04,290 --> 00:02:07,885
****<i>[Tango]</i>

38
00:02:07,961 --> 00:02:11,920
<i>[Crowd Murmuring,</i>
<i>Laughing]</i>

39
00:02:11,998 --> 00:02:14,694
<i>[Mitch Narrating]</i>
<i>One ofhis favorites was the tango.</i>

40
00:02:14,767 --> 00:02:18,498
<i>His own version, of course.</i>
<i>Wherever it came from...</i>

41
00:02:18,571 --> 00:02:21,506
- Come on, join in!
- <i>it wasn't Argentina.</i>

42
00:02:35,355 --> 00:02:38,153
<i>Moments like that...</i>

43
00:02:38,224 --> 00:02:40,954
<i>he could live in forever.</i>

44
00:02:44,497 --> 00:02:48,729
<i>In the summer of 1994,</i>
<i>he began to notice a few things:</i>

45
00:02:48,801 --> 00:02:51,235
- Professor.
- <i>shortness ofbreath...</i>

46
00:02:51,304 --> 00:02:53,932
<i>legs giving him</i>
<i>a little trouble.</i>

47
00:02:54,941 --> 00:02:57,535
<i>But what do you expect at 77?</i>

48
00:02:59,746 --> 00:03:03,045
<i>[Engine Starts]</i>

49
00:03:28,308 --> 00:03:32,574
[Straining]

50
00:03:36,849 --> 00:03:40,546
<i>[Mitch Narrating] The dancing stopped</i>
<i>forever in the summer of 1994.</i>

51
00:03:40,620 --> 00:03:43,555
- [Students Chattering]
- Should we do something?

52
00:03:43,623 --> 00:03:45,887
<i>That was when Morrie</i>
<i>got his death sentence.</i>

53
00:03:54,033 --> 00:03:56,900
Whoa! Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Man, when they fall apart...

54
00:03:56,970 --> 00:03:58,995
<i>these guys really</i>
<i>fall apart, don't they?</i>

55
00:03:59,072 --> 00:04:01,597
This ugly, or is this ugly?
I knew it.

56
00:04:01,674 --> 00:04:04,142
<i>[Man] Everybody's on the floor.</i>
<i>The coaches are out there.</i>

57
00:04:04,210 --> 00:04:06,440
Oh, my... Walter, it's Mitch.
I gotta change the column.

58
00:04:06,512 --> 00:04:08,742
I've got to change
the column, Walter!

59
00:04:08,815 --> 00:04:11,249
<i>[Mitch Narrating] I knew nothing</i>
<i>about what happened to my old professor.</i>

60
00:04:11,317 --> 00:04:14,343
<i>I hadn't seen him since</i>
<i>graduation day 16 years ago.</i>

61
00:04:14,420 --> 00:04:17,856
<i>I promised I'd keep in touch,</i>
<i>but I got busy dancing my own dance.</i>

62
00:04:17,924 --> 00:04:21,655
It's a zoo... Walter, it's a zoo here.
Just hold a space for me, okay?

63
00:04:21,728 --> 00:04:23,958
Give me a break!
Have I ever missed a deadline?

64
00:04:24,030 --> 00:04:28,296
- [All Yelling]
- Janine, hi. Did I wake you, honey?

65
00:04:28,368 --> 00:04:30,632
- <i>Everything I did I did on deadline.</i>
- It's crazy here.

66
00:04:30,703 --> 00:04:34,002
- <i>Everything.</i>
- I just wanna say
I love you and I'm sorry.

67
00:04:34,073 --> 00:04:36,303
Coach said no media
until he talks to the team.

68
00:04:36,376 --> 00:04:38,844
Should've talked to them
before the game.

69
00:04:38,911 --> 00:04:42,677
Yeah... No, we definitely have to talk,
I know. Hang on one second.

70
00:04:42,749 --> 00:04:46,207
- [All Yelling]
- Baby, I gotta go. I love you. Bye-bye.

71
00:04:46,286 --> 00:04:49,221
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>No press.!</i>

72
00:04:49,289 --> 00:04:53,020
<i>Coach, Coach.</i>
<i>Coach, what did you say to the team?</i>
<i>Did the word "discipline"come up?</i>

73
00:04:53,092 --> 00:04:56,118
- [Laughter]
- How about the word "maturity"?

74
00:04:59,699 --> 00:05:02,463
<i>[Mitch Narrating] Sports are always</i>
<i>in season in this country...</i>

75
00:05:02,535 --> 00:05:04,503
<i>and I covered them all...</i>

76
00:05:04,570 --> 00:05:07,733
<i>living in planes and hotels</i>
<i>with a laptop and a cell phone.</i>

77
00:05:07,807 --> 00:05:11,743
<i>I might never have known</i>
<i>what happened to Morrie if I wasn't</i>
<i>always doing six things at once.</i>

78
00:05:11,811 --> 00:05:15,247
Janine, come on. Because I've
been in love with you for seven years.

79
00:05:15,315 --> 00:05:19,115
Doesn't that... Yeah, but in my book,
that is a commitment.

80
00:05:19,185 --> 00:05:21,915
Yeah. Do we have to talk
about this now?

81
00:05:21,988 --> 00:05:24,752
This is the only thing
we ever fight about.

82
00:05:24,824 --> 00:05:27,088
Yeah, because look at what
marriage does to people.

83
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:29,526
I'm not watching it.
It's just on.

84
00:05:29,595 --> 00:05:33,190
<i>Look at what marriage does.</i>
<i>Look at our married friends.</i>
<i>Look at our divorced friends.</i>

85
00:05:33,266 --> 00:05:37,032
Look, I'll be back in Detroit tomorrow.
We'll talk about this then, okay?

86
00:05:37,103 --> 00:05:40,903
Yeah, well, I'll make time.

87
00:05:40,973 --> 00:05:43,635
- [Laughing]
- <i>[Ted Koppel On TV]</i>
<i>Just who is Morrie Schwartz?</i>

88
00:05:43,710 --> 00:05:45,871
<i>And why,</i>
<i>by the end of the night...</i>

89
00:05:45,945 --> 00:05:49,142
<i>are so many of you</i>
<i>going to care about him?</i>

90
00:05:49,215 --> 00:05:51,513
Janine, hang on one second.

91
00:05:51,584 --> 00:05:53,552
<i>[Announcer On TV]</i>
<i>This is</i> ABC News Nightline.

92
00:05:53,619 --> 00:05:57,385
- One second.
- <i>Reporting from Washington, Ted Koppel.</i>

93
00:05:57,457 --> 00:06:01,894
<i>[Ted Koppel]</i>
<i>Tonight, Morrie</i>... <i>Lessons on Living.</i>

94
00:06:01,961 --> 00:06:05,055
<i>Morrie is going to die.</i>

95
00:06:05,131 --> 00:06:08,567
<i>He suffers from a disease</i>
<i>called ALS...</i>

96
00:06:08,634 --> 00:06:11,034
<i>better known</i>
<i>as Lou Gehrig's disease.</i>

97
00:06:11,104 --> 00:06:15,040
<i>Morrie Schwartz is</i>
<i>a retired sociology professor...</i>

98
00:06:15,108 --> 00:06:18,600
<i>from Brandeis University</i>
<i>who is dying of ALS.</i>

99
00:06:18,678 --> 00:06:20,942
<i>Morrie does not have</i>
<i>long to live.</i>

100
00:06:21,013 --> 00:06:25,541
I'm on the last great journey here,
one we all gotta take.

101
00:06:25,618 --> 00:06:28,519
Maybe I can teach people
what to pack for the trip.

102
00:06:28,588 --> 00:06:31,523
- [Click, Dial Tone]
- Janine? Hello?

103
00:06:31,591 --> 00:06:34,151
<i>Or maybe my dying</i>
<i>can be of value...</i>

104
00:06:34,227 --> 00:06:39,665
something we can all learn from,
like a... a human textbook.

105
00:06:39,732 --> 00:06:43,429
<i>I've been a teacher all my life.</i>
<i>You think I'm gonna quit now?</i>

106
00:06:43,503 --> 00:06:45,664
<i>[Morrie Laughing]</i>

107
00:06:45,738 --> 00:06:48,400
<i>[Woman On Phone]</i> Detroit Free Press.
<i>How may I direct your call?</i>

108
00:06:48,474 --> 00:06:51,102
<i>[Woman #2 On Phone] Thank you</i>
<i>for calling the</i> Detroit Free Press.

109
00:06:51,177 --> 00:06:54,544
I'm just getting to work.
Let me call you back, okay?
Very good. How are you?

110
00:06:54,614 --> 00:06:56,912
- Mitch, tomorrow's page.
- Oh, excellent.

111
00:06:56,983 --> 00:06:59,975
- <i>Congratulations.</i>
- On what? The column? It was all right.

112
00:07:00,052 --> 00:07:02,987
A little rushed. Oh, it's official, huh?
Baseball strike is over.

113
00:07:03,055 --> 00:07:05,990
<i>Yeah, which means I need you</i>
<i>in Florida for spring training.</i>

114
00:07:06,058 --> 00:07:08,288
You thought it was rushed?
It read terrific.

115
00:07:08,361 --> 00:07:11,091
- I mean congratulations
on your sweet little TV deal.
- Thank you.

116
00:07:11,164 --> 00:07:14,463
- Walter, local TV, one show a week.
- Books and the radio show...

117
00:07:14,534 --> 00:07:17,503
- Take 20 words out.
- My column comes first, Walter.

118
00:07:17,570 --> 00:07:20,300
- How many hours you got in your day?
- What difference does it make?

119
00:07:20,373 --> 00:07:22,705
- You're spreading yourself
a little thin.
- As long as I deliver.

120
00:07:22,775 --> 00:07:26,040
You think you can find time
to write a piece for the strike
ending tomorrow?

121
00:07:26,112 --> 00:07:28,205
- [Answering Machine]
Hi, this is Janine.
- It's a personal call.

122
00:07:28,281 --> 00:07:30,545
- Say hello toJanine for me.
- Please leave a message.
[Machine Beeps]

123
00:07:30,616 --> 00:07:34,108
Hello. Hello, it's me.
Will you pick up, please?

124
00:07:34,187 --> 00:07:38,123
[Sighs] Janine? Janine, you have
to talk to me sometime.

125
00:07:38,191 --> 00:07:41,388
Will you pick up
the phone, please?

126
00:07:41,461 --> 00:07:43,622
[Sighs]
All right. Um...

127
00:07:43,696 --> 00:07:47,188
I'll, uh...
I'll come by work, I guess.

128
00:07:47,266 --> 00:07:50,497
I love you.

129
00:07:50,570 --> 00:07:52,970
****<i>[Women Harmonizing]</i>

130
00:08:05,818 --> 00:08:09,345
<i>Great column today, man. So,</i>
<i>we finally got baseball back, or what?</i>

131
00:08:09,422 --> 00:08:12,391
I think the fans
should go on strike.

132
00:08:12,458 --> 00:08:15,689
- [Men Laughing]
- What's up, you guys?

133
00:08:15,761 --> 00:08:19,356
Oh, hold it for a second.
Something's not right here.

134
00:08:19,432 --> 00:08:23,562
Take a break for a second, ladies.
Mitch, make yourself useful.
Give me an F-sharp.

135
00:08:23,636 --> 00:08:27,333
- F-sharp.
- [Striking Note]

136
00:08:33,179 --> 00:08:35,113
- Hey.
- Hey.

137
00:08:35,181 --> 00:08:39,174
I've been trying to call. Are you,
uh, ever gonna talk to me again?

138
00:08:39,252 --> 00:08:42,813
I was talking to you last night...
you and the TV...

139
00:08:42,889 --> 00:08:46,086
and then I sort of got the idea
that you didn't want to talk.

140
00:08:46,158 --> 00:08:49,457
I got some bad news last night.
A guy I used to know...

141
00:08:49,529 --> 00:08:53,295
A teacher of mine back in college
is sick. He's gonna die.

142
00:08:53,366 --> 00:08:56,767
Oh, Mitch, I'm sorry.
Were you very close to him?

143
00:08:56,836 --> 00:08:58,929
I used to be, yeah.

144
00:08:59,005 --> 00:09:02,304
<i>Uh, okay, y'all,</i>
<i>let's try this.</i>

145
00:09:02,375 --> 00:09:05,538
[Sighs] We both gotta work
on our phone manners.

146
00:09:05,611 --> 00:09:08,546
[Chuckles]

147
00:09:08,614 --> 00:09:10,548
I love you.

148
00:09:10,616 --> 00:09:13,107
I love you too.

149
00:09:13,185 --> 00:09:16,916
<i>[Man] Okay, let's just</i>
<i>pick this up, ladies.</i>

150
00:09:16,989 --> 00:09:19,116
[TV Sportscaster, Indistinct]

151
00:09:19,191 --> 00:09:22,217
It's not just Morrie. I haven't kept
in touch with anybody from college.

152
00:09:22,295 --> 00:09:24,820
The reunions, the mail...
Who's got time for that stuff?

153
00:09:24,897 --> 00:09:27,798
Well, I wish I had
a teacher like that.

154
00:09:27,867 --> 00:09:31,860
No, he was more than just a teacher.
He was... what... like a force.

155
00:09:31,938 --> 00:09:35,339
<i>[Crowd Cheering]</i>

156
00:09:35,408 --> 00:09:38,070
At this basketball game once,
we were all chanting...

157
00:09:38,144 --> 00:09:40,977
"We're number one!
We're number one," right?

158
00:09:41,047 --> 00:09:45,450
So I see Morrie a couple rows down, he's
eyeing us, he's giving us all this look.

159
00:09:45,518 --> 00:09:47,782
All of a sudden
he stands up and says...

160
00:09:47,853 --> 00:09:50,788
"What's wrong
with being number two?"

161
00:09:50,856 --> 00:09:54,189
He actually wanted to discuss that
right in the middle of the game.

162
00:09:54,260 --> 00:09:56,194
- Thank you.
- <i>Thank you.</i>

163
00:09:56,262 --> 00:10:00,756
Made a really big difference in my life,
and I never even thanked him.

164
00:10:00,833 --> 00:10:05,361
Well, you talk about him
as if he were already dead.
You could still go see him.

165
00:10:05,438 --> 00:10:08,430
He's in Boston. When am I
gonna find time to go to Boston?

166
00:10:08,507 --> 00:10:10,941
Well, make time, if he
meant that much to you.

167
00:10:11,010 --> 00:10:15,538
You're on the road half your life.
Why can't you make time
for one trip to Boston?

168
00:10:15,615 --> 00:10:19,107
- Why are you getting upset?
- Why do you have such a problem
making time in your life...

169
00:10:19,185 --> 00:10:21,949
- Hey, you're that guy
Mitch Albom, right?
- Yeah. Hey...

170
00:10:22,021 --> 00:10:24,387
- <i>Hey, man, I read</i>
<i>your column every day.</i>
- Thank you.

171
00:10:24,457 --> 00:10:28,052
- I've got an idea for a column.
- Guys, I'm in the middle here.

172
00:10:28,127 --> 00:10:32,086
- Gotcha. Hey, we'll talk later?
- I get ideas all the time.

173
00:10:32,164 --> 00:10:35,827
Great. Sorry.

174
00:10:35,901 --> 00:10:38,062
- <i>[TVSportscaster, Indistinct]</i>
- [Sighs] Anyway...

175
00:10:38,137 --> 00:10:40,071
the truth is,
it's too late.

176
00:10:40,139 --> 00:10:43,836
All these years I haven't
sent the guy a postcard.
How am I gonna face him now?

177
00:10:43,909 --> 00:10:47,709
- [Crowd Cheering]
- Mitch, think...

178
00:10:47,780 --> 00:10:51,978
Hey, think of him. Think about
how much it would mean to him.

179
00:10:52,051 --> 00:10:55,145
At least call him.

180
00:10:55,221 --> 00:10:59,920
In hockey last night,
with the play-off berth at stake
and visions of the golden cup...

181
00:10:59,992 --> 00:11:02,984
<i>[Mitch Narrating]</i>
<i>I lived on the phone,</i>
<i>made dozens of calls a day.</i>

182
00:11:03,062 --> 00:11:05,860
<i>Why couldn't I make one</i>
<i>to a dying man?</i>

183
00:11:05,931 --> 00:11:09,594
<i>The simple answer was guilt,</i>
<i>but it was more than that.</i>

184
00:11:09,669 --> 00:11:12,001
<i>I was afraid</i>
<i>of seeing him now.</i>

185
00:11:12,071 --> 00:11:14,039
<i>I had a thing about death.</i>

186
00:11:14,106 --> 00:11:17,234
- Here's my buddy!
- Hey!

187
00:11:17,309 --> 00:11:20,403
Hey. You're one
of the special ones, Mitch.

188
00:11:20,479 --> 00:11:23,505
You're gonna keep in touch,
you gotta promise me.

189
00:11:23,582 --> 00:11:26,073
- I promise.
- <i>[Mitch Narrating]</i>
<i>I failed that promise.</i>

190
00:11:26,152 --> 00:11:28,950
- [Phone Ringing]
- <i>I also had a thing about failure.</i>

191
00:11:29,021 --> 00:11:31,012
- [Janine On Phone] Hello?
- Hey, it's me.

192
00:11:31,090 --> 00:11:33,558
- Hey.
- Well, you were right. I can't work.

193
00:11:33,626 --> 00:11:37,118
I can't even think here. I gotta
do something. About Morrie, I mean.

194
00:11:37,196 --> 00:11:40,131
- Are you gonna go see him?
- Yeah, it's one trip to Boston.

195
00:11:40,199 --> 00:11:44,363
- Quick little visit,
say I'm sorry and say good-bye.
- <i>[Sportscaster, Indistinct]</i>

196
00:11:44,437 --> 00:11:47,372
Well, roll back the tape.
Let me hear the playback again.

197
00:11:47,440 --> 00:11:50,807
- <i>[Sportscaster Continues]</i>
- <i>Okay. Mm-hmm.</i>

198
00:11:50,876 --> 00:11:52,969
- [Tires Skidding]
- Oh, damn it!

199
00:11:53,045 --> 00:11:55,707
- What?
- No, no, no. I just spilled some coffee.

200
00:11:55,781 --> 00:11:59,273
<i>Go-Go ahead.</i>
<i>Let me hear the playback.</i>

201
00:11:59,351 --> 00:12:03,253
Yeah, I'm listening. That sounds fine.
Just go with that.

202
00:12:03,322 --> 00:12:05,984
- What? Take three?
- Yes. Is there a lot more?

203
00:12:06,058 --> 00:12:09,892
- <i>Seven takes.</i>
- <i>You know what? We're gonna</i>
<i>have to do this, uh, later.</i>

204
00:12:18,037 --> 00:12:20,801
Sorry.
Dropped my keys.

205
00:12:23,909 --> 00:12:27,811
It's Mitch.
Mitch Albom?

206
00:12:27,880 --> 00:12:30,348
I called.
I-I spoke to your wife.

207
00:12:30,416 --> 00:12:33,783
I don't get a hug
after 16 years?

208
00:12:39,592 --> 00:12:43,426
[Laughing]

209
00:12:43,496 --> 00:12:46,624
My ol' buddy, you came
to see me at last.

210
00:12:47,933 --> 00:12:50,800
Let's eat.

211
00:12:50,870 --> 00:12:53,703
<i>[Laughing, Sniffing]</i>

212
00:12:53,773 --> 00:12:56,936
Well, I see you still like
to eat as much as ever.

213
00:12:57,009 --> 00:12:59,705
Oh, boy, dig in, huh?
Help yourself.

214
00:12:59,779 --> 00:13:02,373
Come on.
Make yourself comfortable.

215
00:13:02,448 --> 00:13:04,712
- Okay.
- Looks great.

216
00:13:08,487 --> 00:13:10,887
[Slurping]

217
00:13:10,956 --> 00:13:13,618
- <i>[Clears Throat]</i>
- <i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

218
00:13:13,692 --> 00:13:16,320
Well, you look great. Really.

219
00:13:16,395 --> 00:13:20,491
- Really. The same.
- Morrie? Excuse me. Can you talk?

220
00:13:20,566 --> 00:13:24,502
No. Get a name if you could, Connie,
'cause I'm with my buddy now, huh?

221
00:13:24,570 --> 00:13:26,902
I spend half the day
on the telephone.

222
00:13:26,972 --> 00:13:30,237
Now that I'm dying, people are taking
more of an interest in me.

223
00:13:30,309 --> 00:13:34,871
Ah, big celebrity now.
How's that feel being a big TV star?

224
00:13:34,947 --> 00:13:37,882
I mean, you know, you were
always interesting, but, uh...

225
00:13:37,950 --> 00:13:41,750
I thought so.

226
00:13:47,793 --> 00:13:50,023
This-This one class...
Do you remember this, Morrie?

227
00:13:50,095 --> 00:13:53,997
Um, you didn't say anything.
You remember that?
You just stared at us.

228
00:13:54,066 --> 00:13:56,933
- Hmm.
- We all trooped in
with our notebooks ready...

229
00:13:57,002 --> 00:14:00,768
waiting for you to start
casting pearls, and nothing.

230
00:14:00,840 --> 00:14:03,707
<i>Five minutes go by.</i>
<i>Ten minutes.</i>

231
00:14:03,776 --> 00:14:07,075
We started panicking.
"Why isn't the guy saying anything?"

232
00:14:07,146 --> 00:14:10,309
Finally, after like... I think
it was 20 minutes of that...

233
00:14:10,382 --> 00:14:14,250
<i>and we really can't take it anymore,</i>
<i>you say, very quietly</i>...

234
00:14:14,320 --> 00:14:18,086
- "What's happening here?"
- <i>Exactly right.</i>
<i>"What's happening here?"</i>

235
00:14:18,157 --> 00:14:21,092
That's exactly what you said.
You were making a point about silence.

236
00:14:21,160 --> 00:14:25,460
What is it about silence
that makes people uneasy, huh?

237
00:14:25,531 --> 00:14:27,556
Right.

238
00:14:27,633 --> 00:14:31,467
Why do people only feel comfortable
when they're filling the air with words?

239
00:14:31,537 --> 00:14:34,301
Hmm?

240
00:14:34,373 --> 00:14:36,898
[Chuckles]

241
00:14:36,976 --> 00:14:40,969
Should I tell you
what it's like? Dying?

242
00:14:42,781 --> 00:14:45,648
That's another subject that
makes people uncomfortable.

243
00:14:45,718 --> 00:14:49,882
We'll get to it later. You know,
right now I gotta go to the commode.

244
00:14:49,955 --> 00:14:52,651
Are you up to, uh,
giving me a hand?

245
00:14:52,725 --> 00:14:55,159
Um... sure.

246
00:14:55,227 --> 00:14:58,219
Well, now wait a minute.
I better get Connie. It takes an expert.

247
00:14:58,297 --> 00:15:00,492
- <i>[Bell Rings]</i>
- <i>[Morrie] Connie, uh</i>...

248
00:15:00,566 --> 00:15:02,659
[Clears Throat]

249
00:15:02,735 --> 00:15:06,262
You know, dying is just
one thing to be sad about.

250
00:15:06,338 --> 00:15:11,241
<i>Living unhappily,</i>
<i>that's another matter.</i>

251
00:15:12,378 --> 00:15:14,505
See ya in a minute.

252
00:15:14,580 --> 00:15:16,514
Okay.

253
00:15:21,754 --> 00:15:24,314
- [Sighs]
- Are you happy in Detroit?

254
00:15:25,758 --> 00:15:28,283
Yeah. Best town to be in
for a sportswriter.

255
00:15:28,360 --> 00:15:31,921
Football, basketball,
baseball, hockey, you name it.

256
00:15:31,997 --> 00:15:35,660
Are you giving
to your community?

257
00:15:37,536 --> 00:15:39,629
I-I... They're nuts for sports.

258
00:15:39,705 --> 00:15:42,139
You know, that's what I give 'em
every day in my column.

259
00:15:42,207 --> 00:15:44,334
Are you at peace
with yourself?

260
00:15:44,410 --> 00:15:48,471
[Chuckles]
I... I can't complain.

261
00:15:48,547 --> 00:15:51,107
Uh-huh. What
happened to the music?

262
00:15:51,183 --> 00:15:53,651
<i>Wasn't that your passion,</i>
<i>to be a great pianist?</i>

263
00:15:53,719 --> 00:15:55,983
Yeah. Yeah, I gave it a shot,
then I grew up.

264
00:15:56,055 --> 00:15:59,115
You grew up, huh?

265
00:15:59,191 --> 00:16:01,386
Married with kids?

266
00:16:01,460 --> 00:16:05,157
- Uh, no.
- Haven't found anybody
to share your heart with, huh?

267
00:16:05,230 --> 00:16:07,790
No. Yes, I have.
Definitely.

268
00:16:07,866 --> 00:16:10,926
Oh. Not enough
to get married?

269
00:16:11,003 --> 00:16:13,164
Uh, no. Well, y-yes.
I mean, you know, someday.

270
00:16:13,238 --> 00:16:15,798
But, uh, just
when we're both ready.

271
00:16:15,874 --> 00:16:20,334
When you're both ready?
Has she got a name?

272
00:16:20,412 --> 00:16:24,109
- Janine.
- Janine? That's a very beautiful name.

273
00:16:24,183 --> 00:16:28,643
SoJanine shares this "when we're
both ready" thing with you?

274
00:16:28,721 --> 00:16:30,655
No.
[Chuckles]

275
00:16:30,723 --> 00:16:33,021
Uh-huh.
[Laughs]

276
00:16:33,092 --> 00:16:37,085
I can see, Mitch, that we're gonna have
a great deal to talk about.

277
00:16:37,162 --> 00:16:40,563
- What are you writing?
- One more question.

278
00:16:40,632 --> 00:16:44,261
- Yeah?
- You know anything about this
disease that I've got here?

279
00:16:44,336 --> 00:16:47,169
This Lou Gehrig's disease?

280
00:16:47,239 --> 00:16:49,537
It melts ya like a candle,
you know?

281
00:16:49,608 --> 00:16:51,769
In my case,
from the bottom up.

282
00:16:51,844 --> 00:16:56,281
[Straining]
My legs... went first.

283
00:16:56,348 --> 00:16:59,044
Hands will be next...

284
00:16:59,118 --> 00:17:03,054
and eventually
it'll get the whole body.

285
00:17:03,122 --> 00:17:06,023
But you know what I dread?

286
00:17:06,091 --> 00:17:10,460
Someday soon somebody's gonna
have to wipe my ass for me.

287
00:17:12,131 --> 00:17:14,861
<i>But... I'm a lucky man.</i>

288
00:17:14,933 --> 00:17:16,924
- You're lucky?
- <i>Yeah.</i>

289
00:17:17,002 --> 00:17:19,232
I've still got time to learn...

290
00:17:19,304 --> 00:17:22,432
time to say good-bye
to the people I love...

291
00:17:22,508 --> 00:17:25,807
and time to teach
my final course.

292
00:17:25,878 --> 00:17:29,974
- About dying?
- Not about dying! About living!

293
00:17:31,517 --> 00:17:34,577
When you know how to die...

294
00:17:34,653 --> 00:17:37,713
you know how to live.

295
00:17:37,790 --> 00:17:41,453
<i>No, no, no, no, no.</i>
<i>Well, you can't do that, can you?</i>

296
00:17:41,527 --> 00:17:43,961
- Let me hear it again.
- <i>[Toilet Flushing]</i>

297
00:17:44,029 --> 00:17:46,930
- [Morrie Grunting]
- [Connie] I got you.

298
00:17:46,999 --> 00:17:50,332
Dave, you know what? I-I can't do this
right now. I'm really sorry.

299
00:17:50,402 --> 00:17:55,237
Yeah, I'm leaving
for the airport in five minutes.
Can I call you from the car?

300
00:17:55,307 --> 00:17:58,276
Yeah, just give me five minutes, okay?
Thanks a lot, man.

301
00:17:58,343 --> 00:18:00,402
- <i>[Phone Beeps Off]</i>
- <i>[Morrie] Those were my dancing days.</i>

302
00:18:00,479 --> 00:18:02,913
- Did you ever see me dance?
- <i>No.</i>

303
00:18:02,981 --> 00:18:05,745
<i>I saw you do a lot of things,</i>
<i>but, uh, never dance.</i>

304
00:18:05,818 --> 00:18:08,912
That's too bad, because they tell me
it was something to see.

305
00:18:08,987 --> 00:18:11,319
- <i>I'll bet.</i>
- Why don't you keep it?

306
00:18:11,390 --> 00:18:14,587
- Oh, no. Are you sure?
- <i>Yeah.</i>

307
00:18:14,660 --> 00:18:17,185
You remember that nickname
you used to give me?

308
00:18:17,262 --> 00:18:20,527
- Okay, here we go.
- Coach. I called you Coach.

309
00:18:20,599 --> 00:18:23,033
- Yeah.
- [Connie] Easy. Easy. Okay.

310
00:18:23,102 --> 00:18:25,502
Somehow I could never call you
Professor Schwartz.

311
00:18:25,571 --> 00:18:27,971
Well, I liked being called Coach.

312
00:18:28,040 --> 00:18:31,134
Maybe I should've gotten a whistle.
[Chuckles]

313
00:18:31,210 --> 00:18:33,974
- What's the matter? You gotta go?
- Yeah.

314
00:18:34,046 --> 00:18:37,140
- Well, you'll be back.
- Well, I don't know, Coach.

315
00:18:37,216 --> 00:18:42,051
Uh, Detroit is 700 miles, you know?
It's a bit of a time problem.

316
00:18:42,121 --> 00:18:44,715
Well, uh, let me show you
something about time.

317
00:18:44,790 --> 00:18:47,918
[Takes Deep Breath]

318
00:18:47,993 --> 00:18:50,393
[Whispering]
One, two, three, four, five...

319
00:18:50,462 --> 00:18:53,727
six, seven, eight, nine,
ten, eleven, twelve.

320
00:18:53,799 --> 00:18:56,199
[Panting]

321
00:18:56,268 --> 00:18:59,669
Went to 16 last week.

322
00:18:59,738 --> 00:19:02,298
A kid like you...
I bet you go to 100.

323
00:19:02,374 --> 00:19:05,537
You know, it's a good thing
to count your breaths now and then.

324
00:19:05,611 --> 00:19:09,547
Keeps you from putting
things off. Come here.

325
00:19:09,615 --> 00:19:12,812
I'm still your coach.
You promise me...

326
00:19:12,885 --> 00:19:15,410
that you'll come back to see
your old coach, huh?

327
00:19:15,487 --> 00:19:17,421
<i>[Mitch Narrating]</i>
<i>I promised.</i>

328
00:19:17,489 --> 00:19:20,981
<i>I tried not to think about</i>
<i>the last time I promised.</i>

329
00:19:26,932 --> 00:19:29,423
<i>[Engine Starts,</i>
<i>Phone Rings]</i>

330
00:19:29,501 --> 00:19:32,368
- [Phone Beeps]
- Hello?

331
00:19:32,437 --> 00:19:35,338
- <i>[Man On Phone, Indistinct]</i>
- Yeah. No, I have time now.
Let's hear it.

332
00:19:37,376 --> 00:19:39,970
<i>[Mitch] What are the truly</i>
<i>important questions in life...</i>

333
00:19:40,045 --> 00:19:42,104
<i>and where do we go</i>
<i>to find the answers?</i>

334
00:19:42,181 --> 00:19:46,117
<i>There are many paths</i>
<i>on which to seek the truth.</i>
<i>Me, I go to press conferences.</i>

335
00:19:46,185 --> 00:19:48,449
Today in his humble
high school stadium...

336
00:19:48,520 --> 00:19:51,114
I will know the answer
to the question of questions:

337
00:19:51,190 --> 00:19:55,126
<i>What college will two-time all-state</i>
<i>quarterback Shawn Daley...</i>

338
00:19:55,194 --> 00:19:57,560
choose to pursue
his higher education?

339
00:19:57,629 --> 00:19:59,688
And maybe play
a little football.

340
00:19:59,765 --> 00:20:02,791
All you guys
been coverin' my career...

341
00:20:02,868 --> 00:20:06,099
know that I have a dream,
which is to play in the NFL.

342
00:20:06,171 --> 00:20:09,402
[All Cheering]

343
00:20:09,474 --> 00:20:13,410
I been real careful lookin' over
all my scholarship offers...

344
00:20:13,478 --> 00:20:16,038
to choose the best one
to make my dream come true.

345
00:20:16,114 --> 00:20:18,810
<i>Shawn, what are you planning</i>
<i>on getting your degree in?</i>

346
00:20:18,884 --> 00:20:22,342
Well, I'm only gonna be there
two years, then I'll go pro.

347
00:20:22,421 --> 00:20:24,355
- [Cheering]
- <i>[Indistinct]</i>

348
00:20:24,423 --> 00:20:28,052
I mean, I mean, of course
I'm gonna study hard...

349
00:20:28,126 --> 00:20:30,788
and improve my education,
see what happens.

350
00:20:30,862 --> 00:20:33,990
And the truth shall set you free,
or make you a first-round draft choice.

351
00:20:34,066 --> 00:20:36,466
The college I've chose
to go to is...

352
00:20:36,535 --> 00:20:40,494
The moment of truth is here, folks.
On every lip is one prayer:

353
00:20:40,572 --> 00:20:42,733
" Please, God, let it be us."

354
00:20:42,808 --> 00:20:46,835
[All Cheering]

355
00:20:46,911 --> 00:20:49,812
[Laughing]

356
00:20:49,880 --> 00:20:52,314
<i>[Shawn On Tape]</i>
<i>I mean, I mean</i>... - 

357
00:20:52,383 --> 00:20:55,250
- Sounds like another good one.
- Hmm? I'm hungry too.

358
00:20:55,319 --> 00:20:59,016
Two minutes to deadline.
We'll go to dinner. Two minutes.

359
00:21:01,091 --> 00:21:04,322
<i>Can you believe a major press</i>
<i>conference for a high school jock?</i>

360
00:21:04,395 --> 00:21:06,761
Wonder what Morrie
would think of that.

361
00:21:06,830 --> 00:21:09,424
I know what he'd think. What kind
of message does that send...

362
00:21:09,500 --> 00:21:13,937
<i>to kids who actually crack a book, study</i>
<i>their butts off and get scholarships?</i>

363
00:21:14,004 --> 00:21:16,199
And who's gonna hold
a press conference for them?

364
00:21:16,273 --> 00:21:19,436
- Mitch, I'm going to my place tonight.
- Wherever you wanna eat.

365
00:21:19,510 --> 00:21:21,637
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Where you goin'?

366
00:21:21,712 --> 00:21:24,044
It's okay. Keep working.
I'm just tired. I'm gonna go.

367
00:21:24,114 --> 00:21:27,049
What are you talkin' about?
We're goin' to dinner like we
always do. What's the matter?

368
00:21:27,117 --> 00:21:29,176
Nothing. I have a session tomorrow.
I just want to go home.

369
00:21:29,253 --> 00:21:31,721
If we lived together,
you'd be home, but...

370
00:21:31,789 --> 00:21:34,781
Two minutes to deadline, okay? You have
a career. You understand deadlines.

371
00:21:34,858 --> 00:21:37,053
<i>I'm a backup singer.</i>
<i>That's not a career, it's a job.</i>

372
00:21:37,127 --> 00:21:39,061
<i>You could have a great career</i>
<i>if you really wanted it.</i>

373
00:21:39,129 --> 00:21:41,962
- I don't know what I want.
- You're too good to be singing backup.

374
00:21:42,032 --> 00:21:45,058
Mitch, that's not
what I'm talking about.

375
00:21:45,135 --> 00:21:48,866
I can't just keep going on
like this, you know,
waiting for you to fit me in. I-I...

376
00:21:48,939 --> 00:21:52,238
<i>I gotta just think about what I want.</i>
<i>And so do you.</i>

377
00:21:52,309 --> 00:21:55,745
Sorry. I did not mean to get
into this now. I'm gonna call you later.

378
00:21:55,813 --> 00:21:59,374
- [Phone Ringing]
- Janine, please don't go. Janine, wait.

379
00:21:59,450 --> 00:22:02,317
- Can... Obviously, we need to talk.
- [Pager Beeping]

380
00:22:02,386 --> 00:22:05,719
Obviously, we will talk.
I just need one minute, okay?

381
00:22:05,789 --> 00:22:09,486
Please. I love you. It's coming
in one minute. One minute!

382
00:22:09,560 --> 00:22:12,961
God. Please, just give
me a second. Please.

383
00:22:13,030 --> 00:22:16,431
[Tapping Keyboard, Sighs]

384
00:22:16,500 --> 00:22:20,231
<i>[Tape, Indistinct]</i>

385
00:22:21,672 --> 00:22:24,004
- <i>[Phones Ringing]</i>
- It's just not a good time, Mitch.

386
00:22:24,074 --> 00:22:27,066
- Any other time, I'd say okay,
take a few days off, relax.
- No, you wouldn't.

387
00:22:27,144 --> 00:22:30,409
- We got play-offs,
we got tennis, spring training.
- I know.

388
00:22:30,481 --> 00:22:33,609
You wanna take some time, why don't you
cut back from one of your other jobs?

389
00:22:33,684 --> 00:22:36,676
- Walter...
- Do you people work here?
I want you on the road, Mitch.

390
00:22:36,754 --> 00:22:40,281
Walter, I need to be here.
It's personal, okay?

391
00:22:40,357 --> 00:22:42,450
Oh, Janine.
The marriage thing again.

392
00:22:42,526 --> 00:22:46,223
<i>I could recommend</i>
<i>a hell of a counselor.</i>
<i>We got divorced anyway.</i>

393
00:22:46,296 --> 00:22:49,322
- Walter, can I just...
- Look, Mitch, I need you.
Detroit needs you.

394
00:22:49,400 --> 00:22:53,734
I'm sorry about your problems,
but you know what?
The world doesn't stop.

395
00:22:55,105 --> 00:22:58,302
- Okay.
- No, no, no. Come on.
No ground rules.

396
00:22:58,375 --> 00:23:00,502
<i>[Mitch Narrating]</i>
<i>I le</i>ft <i>Janine with promises.</i>

397
00:23:00,577 --> 00:23:02,943
<i>We'd talk. We'd get help</i>
<i>as soon as I got back.</i>

398
00:23:03,013 --> 00:23:06,107
- <i>Meanwhile, Walter was right.</i>
<i>The world didn't stop.</i>
- I'll see you Friday.

399
00:23:06,183 --> 00:23:08,515
Guys, have you got time
for a couple questions?

400
00:23:08,585 --> 00:23:10,917
Guys... Sam, what happened
in the fourth quarter?

401
00:23:10,988 --> 00:23:13,388
Danny, was your knee
bothering you?

402
00:23:13,457 --> 00:23:15,425
<i>[Mitch Narrating]</i>
<i>I remembered my promise to Morrie...</i>

403
00:23:15,492 --> 00:23:17,892
<i>but when would I find time</i>
<i>to keep it?</i>

404
00:23:17,961 --> 00:23:20,725
The strike wasn't about money.
It was never about money.

405
00:23:20,798 --> 00:23:23,426
Gee, how-
how did we miss that?

406
00:23:23,500 --> 00:23:25,593
It was about our worth
as human beings.

407
00:23:25,669 --> 00:23:27,830
<i>Our self-worth</i>
