619
00:36:32,188 --> 00:36:34,247
Yeah, so have I.

620
00:36:34,324 --> 00:36:37,521
Mitch, I don't think we should
see each other anymore.

621
00:36:37,594 --> 00:36:39,960
- [Raucous Laughter]
- What?

622
00:36:40,029 --> 00:36:42,964
- Whoa, wait a minute.
Wait... Let me just...
- No, no, just let me say this.

623
00:36:43,032 --> 00:36:45,865
I can't keep pretending that we're
ever going to be a real couple...

624
00:36:45,935 --> 00:36:48,301
because I know in my heart
that we are never going to be.

625
00:36:48,371 --> 00:36:50,305
- Please don't say that, Janine.
- Mitch.

626
00:36:50,373 --> 00:36:54,139
This is so hard,
but I can't wait anymore.

627
00:36:54,210 --> 00:36:56,144
We just don't want
the same things.

628
00:36:56,212 --> 00:36:58,772
That's not true.
I love you. I...

629
00:36:58,848 --> 00:37:01,976
I know you love me.
And I love you.

630
00:37:02,051 --> 00:37:04,884
[Crying]
But I need more than that.

631
00:37:04,954 --> 00:37:06,922
- Okay.
- <i>[Reporter] Oh, my God.!</i>

632
00:37:06,990 --> 00:37:08,981
Can we please just not
do this on the phone?

633
00:37:09,058 --> 00:37:11,117
I-I will get a plane.
I will come home tonight.

634
00:37:11,194 --> 00:37:13,560
No, Mitch, don't.
I won't be here. It's too late.

635
00:37:13,630 --> 00:37:16,326
- Janine.
- I can't be with you anymore.

636
00:37:16,399 --> 00:37:18,333
I'm sorry.

637
00:37:20,470 --> 00:37:22,904
Hello? Janine? Hello?

638
00:37:22,972 --> 00:37:25,941
<i>Hey, mystery woman.!</i>
<i>He's sneaking her out.!</i>

639
00:37:26,009 --> 00:37:29,843
[All Shouting]

640
00:37:29,913 --> 00:37:32,347
Mitch, come on, let's go.

641
00:37:32,415 --> 00:37:35,851
- Mitch, get the lead out!
- I'm coming. I'm coming.

642
00:37:35,919 --> 00:37:40,151
- Hey, Sergio!
- [Shouting Continues]

643
00:37:42,058 --> 00:37:44,083
[Mitch Grunting]

644
00:37:46,329 --> 00:37:50,595
- [Tires Screeching]
- What the hell am I doing?

645
00:37:52,869 --> 00:37:56,430
<i>[Dispatcher On Radio, Indistinct]</i>

646
00:37:56,506 --> 00:37:59,703
[Chattering]

647
00:38:02,178 --> 00:38:05,705
[Gasping, Wheezing]

648
00:38:07,884 --> 00:38:11,843
[Groaning]

649
00:38:11,921 --> 00:38:15,482
It's all right, sweetheart.
I'm here. I'm right here.

650
00:38:18,795 --> 00:38:21,730
<i>God bless you, sweetheart.</i>

651
00:38:24,033 --> 00:38:27,469
- Ta-da! Food man. Hey, Connie.
- <i>Hey.</i>

652
00:38:27,537 --> 00:38:29,732
<i>Is that Mitch?</i>
<i>Must be Tuesday.</i>

653
00:38:29,806 --> 00:38:32,001
It's Mitch.
How ya doin', Coach?

654
00:38:32,075 --> 00:38:34,600
I hope you haven't eaten already,
'cause I got some very good stuff here.

655
00:38:34,677 --> 00:38:37,373
- Ah, what do you got?
- I got...

656
00:38:37,447 --> 00:38:39,745
some hummus.

657
00:38:39,816 --> 00:38:43,081
- Ahhh.
- I got pita bread, nice and warm.

658
00:38:43,152 --> 00:38:46,747
- Yeah, good.
- I got apple cobbler.

659
00:38:46,823 --> 00:38:52,022
And I got... I got that.

660
00:38:52,095 --> 00:38:56,191
Huh. Tongue!

661
00:38:56,265 --> 00:38:59,200
- Ugh.
- You remembered.

662
00:38:59,268 --> 00:39:02,431
Oh, you don't forget somebody
eating tongue. No, no.

663
00:39:02,505 --> 00:39:06,202
It's like repressed memory. It actually
attacks me in the middle of the night.

664
00:39:06,275 --> 00:39:08,607
- What is that?
- Well, if you're gonna keep giving me...

665
00:39:08,678 --> 00:39:11,408
this meaning of life stuff,
I want to remember it.

666
00:39:11,481 --> 00:39:13,915
- <i>I'd like your voice.</i>
- When I'm dead?

667
00:39:13,983 --> 00:39:17,419
- No, don't say that.
- Mitch, I'm dying.

668
00:39:17,487 --> 00:39:20,923
- It's been established.
- Yeah, yeah.

669
00:39:20,990 --> 00:39:23,788
[Sighs]
That's a pretty big machine, huh.

670
00:39:23,860 --> 00:39:25,953
Must've cost you a fortune.

671
00:39:26,029 --> 00:39:30,295
You know what? This is a stupid
intrusion. I'm gonna put it away.

672
00:39:30,366 --> 00:39:33,460
Hey, you still don't understand.
I want you to remember...

673
00:39:33,536 --> 00:39:36,198
and I want people
to know my story.

674
00:39:36,272 --> 00:39:39,469
That's a very nice machine.
Now, put it back. Go on.

675
00:39:39,542 --> 00:39:42,409
- Okay.
- All right.

676
00:39:43,679 --> 00:39:46,477
Now do you want to hear
a real tragedy?

677
00:39:46,549 --> 00:39:48,517
I can't eat tongue anymore.

678
00:39:50,286 --> 00:39:53,016
But I'm gonna save it.

679
00:39:53,089 --> 00:39:57,116
Maybe I should have it mounted
and hang it in my study, huh?

680
00:40:01,731 --> 00:40:06,430
Okay. So I made a list
of subjects for you to talk about.

681
00:40:06,502 --> 00:40:10,438
All the heavy stuff... death,
love, marriage, family.

682
00:40:10,506 --> 00:40:13,566
Oh, all of the stuff
that you're scared of. Huh.

683
00:40:13,643 --> 00:40:16,771
- Things I want to hear you talk about.
- And you're scared of.

684
00:40:16,846 --> 00:40:20,304
<i>Why be ashamed? Everybody's</i>
<i>afraid of those things.</i>

685
00:40:20,383 --> 00:40:22,476
Add fear to the list.

686
00:40:22,552 --> 00:40:24,486
You don't seem to be scared.

687
00:40:24,554 --> 00:40:27,489
I told you, I have
my early morning moments.

688
00:40:27,557 --> 00:40:31,288
Did you ever know anybody
who was dying?

689
00:40:31,360 --> 00:40:34,261
Yeah, I had an uncle.
Mike. He was young.

690
00:40:34,330 --> 00:40:36,662
He was more
of a brother, really.

691
00:40:36,732 --> 00:40:39,997
<i>Testing, testing.</i>
<i>[Clears Throat]</i>

692
00:40:40,069 --> 00:40:43,835
Mike taught me football, taught me
music, taught me how to drive.

693
00:40:43,906 --> 00:40:47,774
[Chuckles] We used to drive around
this empty lot for hours.

694
00:40:47,844 --> 00:40:50,642
Yeah, he was 42
when he died. Cancer.

695
00:40:50,713 --> 00:40:52,772
And you never
talked about it?

696
00:40:52,849 --> 00:40:56,114
We did what people do, you know?
We pretended nothing was wrong.

697
00:40:56,185 --> 00:40:59,643
- Hmm.
- That's actually when I gave up
music, when Mike died.

698
00:40:59,722 --> 00:41:02,782
- Oh, yeah, when you grew up, huh?
- When I woke up, Coach.

699
00:41:02,859 --> 00:41:06,226
Saw I better get moving if I'm
gonna make anything out of my life.

700
00:41:06,295 --> 00:41:10,493
<i>Well, you made a big success.</i>
<i>I always knew you would. But you ran.</i>

701
00:41:10,566 --> 00:41:14,127
<i>Did you ever stop to think</i>
<i>about what you're running from?</i>

702
00:41:14,203 --> 00:41:17,070
[Turns On Recorder,
Clears Throat]

703
00:41:17,140 --> 00:41:20,132
Okay, what do you want
to tackle first here?

704
00:41:20,209 --> 00:41:22,905
Death? Love? What about
marriage? That's a good one.

705
00:41:22,979 --> 00:41:26,039
- Stickball.
- Stickball?

706
00:41:26,115 --> 00:41:28,811
- Yeah. Did you ever play stickball?
- Uh, no.

707
00:41:28,885 --> 00:41:31,683
Kids don't play stickball anymore,
really. I played Little League.

708
00:41:31,754 --> 00:41:34,052
They don't play anymore?
Oh, that's too bad.

709
00:41:34,123 --> 00:41:36,990
Stickball was what
all the slum kids played.

710
00:41:37,059 --> 00:41:39,663
You know, where I grew up.
Manhattan, the Lower East Side.

711
00:41:40,096 --> 00:41:44,465
- [Children Chattering]
- <i>A broom handle and a rubber ball</i>
<i>was all you needed.</i>

712
00:41:44,534 --> 00:41:47,162
<i>You could play anywhere.</i>

713
00:41:47,237 --> 00:41:51,503
<i>Best place to play was</i>
<i>right outside the candy store</i>
<i>my mother ran for the landlord.</i>

714
00:41:51,574 --> 00:41:54,737
<i>[Woman Shouting In Russian]</i>

715
00:41:54,811 --> 00:41:57,336
- <i>My mother was only 25.</i>
- Moyshe!

716
00:41:57,414 --> 00:42:00,781
- <i>But she was sick</i>
<i>as long as I could remember.</i>
- Moyshe! Moyshe!

717
00:42:00,850 --> 00:42:05,787
I felt if I ignored it, maybe
the sickness would go away.

718
00:42:05,855 --> 00:42:08,085
What happened to her?

719
00:42:08,158 --> 00:42:14,063
She went to the hospital,
and she died there.

720
00:42:14,130 --> 00:42:16,724
[Sobbing]

721
00:42:17,867 --> 00:42:20,631
They sent us a telegram.

722
00:42:22,138 --> 00:42:27,371
<i>My father couldn't read English,</i>
<i>so I had to read it.</i>

723
00:42:29,646 --> 00:42:32,240
[Reading In Yiddish]

724
00:42:46,463 --> 00:42:51,162
<i>[Morrie] That's how I learned</i>
<i>that my mother had died.</i>

725
00:42:51,234 --> 00:42:53,828
<i>I've still got the telegram.</i>

726
00:42:55,472 --> 00:43:00,068
It's all that's left
of my mother, except memories.

727
00:43:00,143 --> 00:43:03,738
So you grew up
with your father?

728
00:43:03,813 --> 00:43:08,750
My father... He was an immigrant
from Russia, a very silent man.

729
00:43:08,818 --> 00:43:12,083
He never showed
what he really felt.

730
00:43:12,155 --> 00:43:16,182
After my mother died, he...
he'd come home from work...

731
00:43:16,259 --> 00:43:18,193
when he could get work...

732
00:43:18,261 --> 00:43:21,025
<i>and he'd never</i>
<i>come in the house.</i>

733
00:43:21,097 --> 00:43:25,466
<i>He'd stay outside,</i>
<i>read the newspaper...</i>

734
00:43:25,535 --> 00:43:27,935
<i>until he knew I was asleep.</i>

735
00:43:28,004 --> 00:43:31,496
<i>What was he feeling?</i>
<i>See, I never knew.</i>

736
00:43:31,574 --> 00:43:35,203
What... Was he in pain?
Was he suffering? I...

737
00:43:35,278 --> 00:43:39,044
All I knew was that...
that I needed his love.

738
00:43:39,115 --> 00:43:43,347
I needed him to hold me
so I wouldn't be so afraid.

739
00:43:43,419 --> 00:43:45,353
<i>[Sighs]</i>

740
00:43:45,421 --> 00:43:48,151
Never got it, though, did you?

741
00:43:48,224 --> 00:43:50,658
No. Not from him.

742
00:43:51,861 --> 00:43:54,159
He remarried
about a year later.

743
00:43:56,132 --> 00:43:58,532
[Speaking Russian]

744
00:43:58,601 --> 00:44:01,798
<i>[Morrie] 'Course I resented her</i>
<i>at first. I pushed her away.</i>

745
00:44:01,871 --> 00:44:03,964
[Yiddish]

746
00:44:04,040 --> 00:44:07,498
<i>But she was</i>
<i>a wonderful woman.</i>

747
00:44:07,577 --> 00:44:11,707
<i>And from her, a</i>ft<i>er I stopped being</i>
<i>such a little smart-ass...</i>

748
00:44:11,781 --> 00:44:16,718
- ** [Singing In Yiddish]
- <i>I finally began to get</i>
<i>the love that I'd been missing.</i>

749
00:44:16,786 --> 00:44:19,721
** [Singing Continues]

750
00:44:21,391 --> 00:44:25,191
<i>[Mitch] What about your father?</i>
<i>Did things get better?</i>

751
00:44:25,261 --> 00:44:27,752
<i>[Morrie]</i>
<i>He did something...</i>

752
00:44:27,831 --> 00:44:31,232
<i>God, I found</i>
<i>very, very hard to forgive.</i>

753
00:44:31,301 --> 00:44:34,600
He said I had a new mother...

754
00:44:34,671 --> 00:44:37,606
and that I should forget.

755
00:44:37,674 --> 00:44:41,132
He wouldn't even let me talk
about my mother.

756
00:44:41,211 --> 00:44:44,840
It was like she'd never existed.
[Sobbing]

757
00:44:48,785 --> 00:44:51,379
- Need help here.
- I think we should stop.

758
00:44:51,454 --> 00:44:53,979
No. I want you to hear this.

759
00:44:54,057 --> 00:44:56,855
My father was afraid of love.

760
00:44:56,926 --> 00:44:59,861
He couldn't give it, and
he couldn't receive it either.

761
00:44:59,929 --> 00:45:02,693
- Maybe that's worse.
- Morrie, we should stop.

762
00:45:02,765 --> 00:45:05,529
Not letting
ourselves be loved...

763
00:45:05,602 --> 00:45:10,096
because we're too afraid of giving
ourselves to someone we might lose.

764
00:45:10,173 --> 00:45:12,903
[Gasping]

765
00:45:12,976 --> 00:45:16,275
[Gasping Continues]

766
00:45:16,346 --> 00:45:20,305
- Um... Connie! Connie!
- [Hissing]

767
00:45:20,383 --> 00:45:23,580
Ahh. Connie! Connie!

768
00:45:23,653 --> 00:45:26,713
[Bell Ringing]

769
00:45:26,789 --> 00:45:29,656
<i>You're okay. Okay.</i>

770
00:45:29,726 --> 00:45:32,752
- [Groaning]
- That's it. Okay, breathe.

771
00:45:32,829 --> 00:45:36,230
<i>Good. Good.</i>
<i>Okay. You're okay.</i>

772
00:45:36,299 --> 00:45:39,632
<i>[Morrie Sighing]</i>

773
00:45:45,108 --> 00:45:48,134
[Pager Beeping]

774
00:45:53,082 --> 00:45:55,016
[Sighs]

775
00:45:55,084 --> 00:45:57,018
<i>[Phone Rings]</i>

776
00:45:57,086 --> 00:46:00,112
Where the hell are you?
You're supposed to be
in New York for the play-offs.

777
00:46:00,189 --> 00:46:02,589
Yeah, I'll be there
tonight, Walter.

778
00:46:02,659 --> 00:46:06,925
Oh, it's only the play-offs.
Hey, what is this number?
How many jobs have you got?

779
00:46:06,996 --> 00:46:09,089
It's got nothing
to do with work. I just...

780
00:46:09,165 --> 00:46:11,725
- I thought that the column came first.
- This is personal, okay?

781
00:46:11,801 --> 00:46:13,735
I just need
a little bit of time...

782
00:46:13,803 --> 00:46:15,896
You have time
for everybody but me.

783
00:46:15,972 --> 00:46:19,840
- I got plenty of guys here
dyin' to write a column.
- What is that supposed to mean?

784
00:46:19,909 --> 00:46:22,537
- You think Detroit
can't live without you?
- Why don't you find out.

785
00:46:22,612 --> 00:46:26,480
You know that comp time you've got
built up? I suggest that you take it.

786
00:46:26,549 --> 00:46:30,007
- You do whatever the hell you want to.
- Well, fine, I will.

787
00:46:30,086 --> 00:46:31,986
Fine!

788
00:46:34,657 --> 00:46:37,558
<i>[Toilet Flushing]</i>

789
00:46:38,828 --> 00:46:41,023
[Connie]
Here we go.

790
00:46:41,097 --> 00:46:44,123
We'll soon have you
back in your chair.

791
00:46:44,200 --> 00:46:48,193
<i>Okay, I'm just gonna</i>
<i>get your feet clear.</i>

792
00:46:48,271 --> 00:46:51,638
<i>One. Okay, you're all set.</i>

793
00:46:51,708 --> 00:46:55,303
Connie. Connie,
show me how to do that?

794
00:46:55,378 --> 00:46:59,212
- Mm-hmm.
- Okay. Come on over here.

795
00:47:00,416 --> 00:47:02,907
<i>Okay, now bend down.</i>

796
00:47:02,986 --> 00:47:06,319
- Slide your arms under his
like you're lifting a log.
- Okay.

797
00:47:06,389 --> 00:47:09,256
- Okay, now he can't
help you at all, honey.
- Like this?

798
00:47:09,325 --> 00:47:11,316
- Yeah, it has to be all you.
- All right.

799
00:47:11,394 --> 00:47:14,056
- Now lift. Okay.
- [Morrie Groaning]

800
00:47:14,130 --> 00:47:16,997
- Sorry. I'll get it.
- Okay, let him move.

801
00:47:17,066 --> 00:47:19,591
Okay, okay, good.
All right, I got ya.

802
00:47:19,669 --> 00:47:22,536
- I got ya. Okay.
- [Groaning Continues]

803
00:47:22,605 --> 00:47:26,097
- Okay.
- <i>You got him.</i>

804
00:47:26,175 --> 00:47:29,440
[Groans, Sighs]

805
00:47:29,512 --> 00:47:32,072
- Sorry. You all right?
- Oh, yeah.

806
00:47:32,148 --> 00:47:35,549
Sorry. I'll get better at it.

807
00:47:35,618 --> 00:47:37,779
[Morrie Mutters]

808
00:47:41,290 --> 00:47:44,953
Don't look so sad
because I'm gonna die, Mitch.

809
00:47:45,028 --> 00:47:47,758
Everybody's gonna die.
Even you.

810
00:47:47,830 --> 00:47:49,957
<i>But most people don't believe it.</i>

811
00:47:50,033 --> 00:47:52,365
They should have a bird
on their shoulder.

812
00:47:52,435 --> 00:47:54,869
<i>That's what the Buddhists do.</i>

813
00:47:54,937 --> 00:47:57,963
Just imagine a little bird
on your shoulder...

814
00:47:58,041 --> 00:48:02,501
and every day you say, "Is this the day
I'm gonna die, little bird?

815
00:48:02,578 --> 00:48:07,811
" Huh? Am I ready? Am I leading
the life I want to lead?

816
00:48:07,884 --> 00:48:11,718
<i>Am I the person that I want to be?"</i>

817
00:48:13,790 --> 00:48:18,159
If we accept the fact
that we can die at any time,
we'd lead our lives differently.

818
00:48:18,227 --> 00:48:22,459
<i>So every day you say,</i>
<i>"Is this the day?"</i>

819
00:48:22,532 --> 00:48:25,501
- Hmm?
- One sec. One sec.

820
00:48:25,568 --> 00:48:27,559
<i>Okay, go ahead.</i>

821
00:48:27,637 --> 00:48:30,572
[Morrie On Tape] If you did
have a bird on your shoulder...

822
00:48:30,640 --> 00:48:34,269
you wouldn't put off the things
closest to your heart.

823
00:48:34,343 --> 00:48:37,312
<i>[Mitch Narrating] I didn't need</i>
<i>the recorder to hear his voice anymore.</i>

824
00:48:37,380 --> 00:48:39,610
<i>It was always in my mind now.</i>

825
00:48:39,682 --> 00:48:42,947
<i>I thought ofhis helpless weight</i>
<i>in my arms as I li</i>ft<i>ed him</i>... - 

826
00:48:43,019 --> 00:48:45,385
<i>that frail, failing body...</i>

827
00:48:45,455 --> 00:48:48,424
<i>and the voice, the spirit inside...</i>

828
00:48:48,491 --> 00:48:50,425
<i>at its ruthless mercy.</i>

829
00:49:04,507 --> 00:49:08,466
- [Muttering]
- <i>And time whooshing past...</i>

830
00:49:08,544 --> 00:49:11,741
<i>like thejet stream</i>
<i>outside my window.</i>

831
00:49:11,814 --> 00:49:14,442
<i>And notjust for Morrie.</i>

832
00:49:16,752 --> 00:49:20,688
<i>I'd taken Morrie's advice.</i>
<i>I'd put a bird on my shoulder.</i>

833
00:49:34,637 --> 00:49:38,801
<i>O-Oh, yeah. Come on in, baby.</i>
<i>Let's hear it back.</i>

834
00:49:41,110 --> 00:49:43,135
- Oh, hey, Mitch Man, I didn't see you.
- Hey.

835
00:49:43,212 --> 00:49:47,046
- <i>So, what do you think?</i>
